## Security Checklist

### Authentication & Authorization

- [ ] Authentication method chosen (OAuth 2.0 / JWT / Sessions / MFA)
- [ ] Passwords hashed (bcrypt/scrypt/argon2, NOT plain SHA)
- [ ] Session tokens are cryptographically secure
- [ ] RBAC or ABAC model defined
- [ ] Least-privilege principle applied

### Data Protection

- [ ] Sensitive data fields identified (passwords, API keys, PII)
- [ ] Sensitive data encrypted at rest (e.g., PostgreSQL pgcrypto)
- [ ] Sensitive data encrypted in transit (TLS 1.2+)
- [ ] PII handling documented (retention, deletion, GDPR compliance)
- [ ] No sensitive data logged to stdout/files

### API Security

- [ ] HTTPS enforced (HTTP redirects to HTTPS)
- [ ] CORS policy defined (allowed origins)
- [ ] CSRF protection implemented (if using sessions)
- [ ] Input validation prevents SQL injection, XSS, XXE
- [ ] Rate limiting prevents brute force attacks

### Infrastructure & Deployment

- [ ] Secrets management strategy defined (env vars / vault / KMS)
- [ ] No credentials committed to version control
- [ ] Database backups automated and tested
- [ ] Access logs enable security audits
- [ ] Monitoring for suspicious activity configured

### Third-Party Risk

- [ ] All external APIs documented in ctx (Project Context)
- [ ] Third-party SLAs and security posture reviewed
- [ ] API keys/tokens stored securely (not in code)
- [ ] Third-party libraries scanned for known vulnerabilities

